00:38:42,465 --> 00:38:47,469
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the remainder, uh, one of four and one of fives are two and three families.

386
00:38:48,790 --> 00:38:55,795
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the, uh, number that was left seniors in other parcels, there was nothing to tie them to in terms of ownership.

387
00:38:56,115 --> 00:39:00,578
[SPEAKER_02]: So they were living in, I would assume they were in apartments or some kind of a mixed use apartment where they rented.

388
00:39:06,574 --> 00:39:08,155
[SPEAKER_02]: This just is from the state.

389
00:39:08,195 --> 00:39:12,436
[SPEAKER_02]: This is a state level tax relief program.

390
00:39:13,317 --> 00:39:15,858
[SPEAKER_02]: So anyone could apply for this.

391
00:39:16,018 --> 00:39:25,402
[SPEAKER_02]: If they're a senior, there's certain credentials that need to be met that are spelled out there in terms of income limits and the assessed value on the home.

392
00:39:26,342 --> 00:39:34,185
[SPEAKER_02]: And also if there's a renter, the percentage of annual rent that 10% of the annual income.

393
00:39:40,650 --> 00:39:50,096
[SPEAKER_02]: So as I said at the beginning, this now gets into, this is more concrete numbers because we're working with 26 values now.

394
00:39:50,156 --> 00:40:03,584
[SPEAKER_02]: So this is just saying hypothetically, if we added 440 million to the fiscally 26 levy, which we know, and it's already been approved by the DOR, this is what would have happened.

395
00:40:05,197 --> 00:40:16,282
[SPEAKER_02]: And the percentages are the same across all the different classes, but the numbers vary because of the averages.

396
00:40:16,442 --> 00:40:17,923
[SPEAKER_02]: So the averages are across the top.

397
00:40:18,683 --> 00:40:22,425
[SPEAKER_02]: The second line down would be the, it's the average tax bill.

398
00:40:22,505 --> 00:40:30,188
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's just our fiscal 26 residential rate tie into the average assessed for each class.

399
00:40:31,413 --> 00:40:37,995
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the next one down would be what the tax bill would have been if we increased the levy.

400
00:40:38,835 --> 00:40:42,216
[SPEAKER_02]: And then it's just the difference in terms of dollars and the difference in terms of percentage.

401
00:40:47,437 --> 00:40:49,037
[SPEAKER_02]: Same math, but again, at the 532 instead of the 440.

402
00:40:53,443 --> 00:40:55,106
[SPEAKER_02]: And as you can see, the percentage is going up.

403
00:40:55,327 --> 00:41:00,657
[SPEAKER_02]: And then at the 607 would be the highest percentage, roughly 23% across the residential classes.

404
00:41:08,887 --> 00:41:10,568
[SPEAKER_02]: So this now is the levy.

405
00:41:12,009 --> 00:41:24,619
[SPEAKER_02]: So as I said before, the tax that's tied to the debt exclusion or the amount borrowed is a constant until the debt falls off because the debt payments will be a constant.

406
00:41:24,799 --> 00:41:35,487
[SPEAKER_02]: But the percent of the levy will gradually fall off after it peaks in 33 because new growth continues to increase because we still increase the levy by prop two and a half.

407
00:41:36,720 --> 00:41:49,995
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think there was some people that thought that the tax bill would start to decrease after 33 and it's not true in the sense that the tax is tied to the amount borrowed and the amount borrowed is a constant.

408
00:42:00,240 --> 00:42:04,981
[SPEAKER_02]: And then again, same slide, just going through the different numbers here.

409
00:42:05,101 --> 00:42:06,141
[SPEAKER_02]: This is at 532,000.

410
00:42:06,961 --> 00:42:13,783
[SPEAKER_02]: So this would peak at roughly 13% and then gradually fall after fiscal 33 in terms of percent of the levy.

411
00:42:17,764 --> 00:42:23,865
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the same here at 607, that would peak roughly around 15% of the levy and then start to gradually fall after 33.

412
00:42:30,272 --> 00:42:37,094
[SPEAKER_02]: And then this here is just the debt itself and how it would be if the percent of the levy was borrowed.

413
00:42:37,134 --> 00:42:44,936
[SPEAKER_02]: And as you can see, in fiscal 33 is when it peaks and it stays that way until the debt is paid off.

414
00:42:49,678 --> 00:42:52,258
[SPEAKER_02]: Same for the 532 million.

415
00:42:52,278 --> 00:42:54,379
[SPEAKER_02]: So these would be the numbers tied to that amount.

416
00:42:59,525 --> 00:43:05,166
[SPEAKER_02]: And then lastly, the 607 and the numbers tied to that amount and the percent of the levy.

417
00:43:11,248 --> 00:43:15,609
[SPEAKER_02]: And then again, we went with fiscal 26 because that was our last known year.

418
00:43:16,569 --> 00:43:21,511
[SPEAKER_02]: So the fiscal 26 tax, this is just no class.

419
00:43:21,551 --> 00:43:24,151
[SPEAKER_02]: This is just if your house fell at 400, 500, 600, all the way up to 2.2 million.

420
00:43:27,680 --> 00:43:32,044
[SPEAKER_02]: This is what your fiscal 26 real estate tax would have been in the second column.

421
00:43:33,885 --> 00:43:41,332
[SPEAKER_02]: The third column is with the debt exclusion added at 440 million and the impact would just be the difference.

422
00:43:41,992 --> 00:43:43,614
[SPEAKER_02]: And then that's the annual difference.

423
00:43:43,674 --> 00:43:46,356
[SPEAKER_02]: The second to last column going left to right.

424
00:43:47,257 --> 00:43:52,181
[SPEAKER_02]: And the last column is just your annual tax impact divided by 12, which gives you your monthly.

425
00:43:57,215 --> 00:44:03,518
[SPEAKER_02]: So again, 532 million, same slide, just a different amount added to the levy.

426
00:44:04,098 --> 00:44:08,360
[SPEAKER_02]: And those are the numbers for each dwelling value.

427
00:44:13,403 --> 00:44:20,526
[SPEAKER_02]: And lastly, 607 million, this would be the most impactful and numbers again for the dwelling values.

