[SPEAKER_15]: I have solar that offsets a lot of that.

535
00:53:42,788 --> 00:53:53,075
[SPEAKER_15]: So I'm curious where we're getting this big number where we're tripling, quadrupling what we're currently paying at the current high school to get this giant number when I would assume we're gonna have a much more efficient building.

536
00:53:53,763 --> 00:54:08,728
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, you get much more efficient building, but it's you have to also remember part of the service at the high school right now is gas not electric because the heat is not coming through electric.

537
00:54:09,248 --> 00:54:11,149
[SPEAKER_20]: So you're converting all your heat.

538
00:54:11,249 --> 00:54:12,309
[SPEAKER_20]: You're electrifying.

539
00:54:13,070 --> 00:54:13,810
[SPEAKER_20]: It's all.

540
00:54:14,995 --> 00:54:16,976
[SPEAKER_20]: to equipment choices.

541
00:54:18,337 --> 00:54:25,521
[SPEAKER_20]: There is a new building in the city of Medford that my feeling is the incorrect choice as an HVAC system was made.

542
00:54:25,581 --> 00:54:32,184
[SPEAKER_20]: That's the building where the city is paying $220,000 a year for electric, for 40,000.

543
00:54:32,284 --> 00:54:33,625
[SPEAKER_15]: Can you say what that building is?

544
00:54:34,686 --> 00:54:35,466
[SPEAKER_20]: I'd rather not.

545
00:54:36,046 --> 00:54:37,467
[SPEAKER_20]: Maybe privately I could tell you.

546
00:54:38,468 --> 00:54:40,409
[SPEAKER_20]: Isn't it a matter of public record, Paul?

547
00:54:42,216 --> 00:54:44,377
[SPEAKER_20]: If the mayor wants me to talk about it, I can.

548
00:54:44,397 --> 00:54:47,479
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, it'd be helpful.

549
00:54:47,499 --> 00:54:48,619
[SPEAKER_15]: We've built a few new buildings.

550
00:54:48,719 --> 00:54:50,540
[SPEAKER_15]: It'd be helpful to know which one is a meeting.

551
00:54:50,700 --> 00:54:57,084
[SPEAKER_20]: In my feeling, the police station, they picked the incorrect HVAC system for that building.

552
00:54:57,904 --> 00:55:03,247
[SPEAKER_20]: That building is eating electric in the winter.

553
00:55:03,988 --> 00:55:07,110
[SPEAKER_20]: It's built that electric boilers come on in the winter.

554
00:55:08,190 --> 00:55:10,433
[SPEAKER_20]: They come on when it hits 32 degrees.

555
00:55:10,633 --> 00:55:12,475
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, we're in the Northeast.

556
00:55:13,176 --> 00:55:16,059
[SPEAKER_20]: Our winter is usually 32 degrees or below.

557
00:55:16,600 --> 00:55:25,069
[SPEAKER_20]: So the electric boilers are on almost 24, 7 in that building, starting sometime in December through probably March.

558
00:55:25,590 --> 00:55:28,933
[SPEAKER_20]: So the amount of electric that building is used.

559
00:55:29,754 --> 00:55:48,158
[SPEAKER_20]: But when they built the DPW in the library, they made much better HVAC choices and much more efficient choices, all electrified, but the buildings use much less electric to not only cool, but also to heat.

560
00:55:48,278 --> 00:55:57,020
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's why I'm saying is that you need to be very careful when designing a building and when picking HVAC systems.

561
00:55:57,601 --> 00:55:59,141
[SPEAKER_20]: They really need to be vetted.

562
00:56:00,262 --> 00:56:04,646
[SPEAKER_20]: And you really need to ask the tough questions about usage.

563
00:56:05,286 --> 00:56:09,350
[SPEAKER_20]: And am I getting my dollars for the usage?

564
00:56:09,450 --> 00:56:13,714
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, a high school building is open what 1617 hours a day, almost 7 days a week.

565
00:56:13,734 --> 00:56:15,215
[SPEAKER_20]: So it's using a lot of energy.

566
00:56:15,235 --> 00:56:15,336
[SPEAKER_20]: So.

567
00:56:22,146 --> 00:56:23,387
[SPEAKER_20]: It's an important choice.

568
00:56:23,447 --> 00:56:31,116
[SPEAKER_20]: It doesn't seem like an important choice, but it's a very important choice for money savings.

569
00:56:31,697 --> 00:56:39,766
[SPEAKER_20]: You electrify, but you can also realize some savings if you make some very good, wise choices.

570
00:56:41,463 --> 00:56:42,084
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay, thank you.

571
00:56:42,124 --> 00:56:43,625
[SPEAKER_15]: And I just have two more points, Jenny, if I could.

572
00:56:45,246 --> 00:56:49,950
[SPEAKER_15]: One, you know, I appreciate the inclusion of the senior data in the presentation.

573
00:56:49,970 --> 00:56:52,252
[SPEAKER_15]: I think I understand the point that was trying to be made there.

574
00:56:52,312 --> 00:56:57,897
[SPEAKER_15]: I would have liked to see the inclusion as far as student data, you know, how many students are going to be served by this high school.

575
00:56:58,298 --> 00:57:00,179
[SPEAKER_15]: And then also, I think it's a little frustrating to

576
00:57:01,280 --> 00:57:08,905
[SPEAKER_15]: be a little leading towards the end there as far as the capital budget and debt exclusion and then the budget for our FTEs.

577
00:57:09,445 --> 00:57:13,067
[SPEAKER_15]: Medford historically until two years ago, we've never had an override.

578
00:57:13,087 --> 00:57:17,330
[SPEAKER_15]: We don't go to the community to ask for that override every few years like Lexington does.

579
00:57:17,390 --> 00:57:25,015
[SPEAKER_15]: So I think it's a little frustrating to compare us to cities when it's convenient to make a certain point and not otherwise, but that's just my last point.

580
00:57:25,515 --> 00:57:25,955
[SPEAKER_15]: So thank you.

581
00:57:27,997 --> 00:57:28,557
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Nicole.

582
00:57:29,692 --> 00:57:47,683
[SPEAKER_17]: I would also encourage people to stay on and listen to our project team talk about life cycle cost analysis and the actual assumptions that have gone into the pricing of the building and what the continuity and the lifespan and the payoff of those are because they are in conflict with what was just presented.

583
00:57:47,743 --> 00:57:50,585
[SPEAKER_17]: So please stay tuned for that later in the presentation.

584
00:57:52,786 --> 00:57:58,510
[SPEAKER_17]: Other members of the committee, are there, does anyone else have questions before I take questions from the public?

585
00:58:06,885 --> 00:58:11,848
[SPEAKER_17]: Okay, I will go to the public Michelle Barkson.

586
00:58:16,651 --> 00:58:19,413
[SPEAKER_17]: And if you can say your name and address for the record, you have 3 minutes.

587
00:58:20,688 --> 00:58:22,349
[SPEAKER_10]: Hi, I'm Michelle Barkson.

588
00:58:22,449 --> 00:58:23,849
[SPEAKER_10]: I live at 23 Diane Road.

589
00:58:24,710 --> 00:58:31,953
[SPEAKER_10]: First of all, I just want to say how very excited I am and thank everybody on the committee for all this incredible work and the amount of time that it is.

590
00:58:33,373 --> 00:58:37,635
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm a teacher actually in Lexington, so I wanted to kind of center some of my points around that.

591
00:58:38,555 --> 00:58:44,879
[SPEAKER_10]: So first of all, a functioning high school is just imperative, not only for students, but really for a full community.

592
00:58:44,899 --> 00:58:54,005
[SPEAKER_10]: I think the high school and the school system is the cornerstone of a community, and I would hope that all of Medford can rally behind that.

593
00:58:55,126 --> 00:58:57,167
[SPEAKER_10]: Second, I want to clarify some points.

594
00:58:57,287 --> 00:59:02,490
[SPEAKER_10]: Lexington did not lose 65 positions because of a debt exclusion, because the new high schools passed.

595
00:59:02,550 --> 00:59:04,692
[SPEAKER_10]: Those were totally separate funding mechanisms.

596
00:59:05,292 --> 00:59:09,875
[SPEAKER_10]: The reason we lost a lot of positions, about 85% of them had to do with low enrollment.

597
00:59:11,155 --> 00:59:13,017
[SPEAKER_10]: We're losing students at Lexington.

598
00:59:13,057 --> 00:59:14,437
[SPEAKER_10]: That's why we're cutting positions.

599
00:59:14,537 --> 00:59:19,620
[SPEAKER_10]: So I just want to clarify that the new high school had nothing to do with the loss of positions and

600
00:59:21,161 --> 00:59:35,731
[SPEAKER_10]: I just wanted to make sure people aren't afraid to pass a debt exclusion here, thinking that it would end up somehow cutting teacher positions, because the debt exclusion is an entirely separate funding mechanism than the yearly budget, which is what staffing is paid under.

601
00:59:36,572 --> 00:59:41,195
[SPEAKER_10]: So my question to perhaps the mayor, or I guess anybody that can answer this.

602
00:59:42,156 --> 00:59:44,577
[SPEAKER_10]: So we just saw a lot of competing priorities.

603
00:59:45,698 --> 00:59:58,245
[SPEAKER_10]: I also, I guess since I'm talking about the debt exclusion, my other question is, I'm wondering why the debt exclusion would actually affect all of these other city services considering, like I said, it's a separate funding mechanism.

604
00:59:58,265 --> 01:00:04,668
[SPEAKER_10]: But I guess my larger question is, what are we doing as a city to bring down the cost?

605
01:00:04,688 --> 01:00:05,689
[SPEAKER_10]: We need a new high school.

606
01:00:06,029 --> 01:00:08,650
[SPEAKER_10]: Our students deserve the best experience they can.

607
01:00:08,770 --> 01:00:11,652
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm so proud of the VOC and the comprehensive that we have here.

608
01:00:12,172 --> 01:00:12,753
[SPEAKER_10]: So instead of

609
01:00:13,753 --> 01:00:18,477
[SPEAKER_10]: talking about all these other priorities, my question is what are we going to do to make sure that this gets funded?

610
01:00:20,218 --> 01:00:22,060
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you and again thank you for everyone's time.

611
01:00:28,065 --> 01:00:29,266
[SPEAKER_30]: I guess I can answer that.

612
01:00:29,366 --> 01:00:36,632
[SPEAKER_30]: I think the presentation was to show the lack of capacity in our debt just so everybody is aware.

613
01:00:37,372 --> 01:00:38,854
[SPEAKER_30]: The city is assessing the Curtis

614
01:00:43,187 --> 01:00:49,849
[SPEAKER_30]: a price tag on what that building will be to rehab and see what services we can shift to the Curtis Tufts.

615
01:00:51,649 --> 01:00:59,832
[SPEAKER_30]: But this presentation was really just to show, to give nothing more than facts based on our evaluation of the numbers.

616
01:01:05,933 --> 01:01:09,434
[SPEAKER_17]: I see Zachary Chertok as the next hand.

617
01:01:10,995 --> 01:01:12,215
[SPEAKER_17]: Name and address for the record, please.

618
01:01:13,468 --> 01:01:15,411
[SPEAKER_28]: Zachary Chertock five all month street.

619
01:01:16,392 --> 01:01:31,569
[SPEAKER_28]: First I want to thank the mayor for assembling the team here and presenting what she did regarding the cost that the city's entire debt services, and what the impact of adding that sizable exclusion would be to our ability to continue not just funding our entire operations with leverage.

620
01:01:32,350 --> 01:01:45,142
[SPEAKER_28]: but also you know looking at what it would do to push us to the to the edge of that leverage and what that would mean for our ability to exercise that leverage for a multitude of things that this city has to serve as not just the high school.

621
01:01:46,183 --> 01:01:56,032
[SPEAKER_28]: I also appreciate that after the effort to show what the impact would be to residents based on range cost projections at the high middle and low in the absence of committed costs for the high school project at this point.

622
01:01:56,853 --> 01:02:05,338
[SPEAKER_28]: The numbers are sizable and I would ask the committee to really honor the mayor's request to think seriously through the cost what's nice to have versus what's imperative.

623
01:02:05,358 --> 01:02:19,527
[SPEAKER_28]: And really right size this especially relative to the number of students it's going to serve because the student limit set by the, the MSBA is public you can see it and what we're looking at relative to some of the comparable projects in the last five years.

624
01:02:20,567 --> 01:02:25,370
[SPEAKER_28]: is to serve a smaller number of students with an equal, if not bigger capacity building.

625
01:02:25,390 --> 01:02:27,892
[SPEAKER_28]: And that includes the DESC for the vocational school.

626
01:02:28,773 --> 01:02:34,136
[SPEAKER_28]: So I would really ask that the two sides work together towards what the mayor has asked in her last slide.

627
01:02:34,336 --> 01:02:39,140
[SPEAKER_28]: And that's also coming from someone whose relatives were recently involved on the Salem High School project.

628
01:02:39,480 --> 01:02:39,860
[SPEAKER_28]: Thank you.

629
01:02:39,880 --> 01:02:43,142
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

630
01:02:43,162 --> 01:02:44,023
[SPEAKER_11]: Ellen.

631
01:02:52,983 --> 01:02:53,944
[SPEAKER_26]: name and address for the record?

632
01:02:54,264 --> 01:02:55,585
[SPEAKER_26]: Yep, my name's Ellen Rushman.

633
01:02:55,625 --> 01:02:58,767
[SPEAKER_26]: My address is 52 Stickney Road.

634
01:02:59,647 --> 01:03:06,931
[SPEAKER_26]: I guess I'm pretty disappointed and confused by the presentation that we just heard from the mayor and her staff.

635
01:03:07,392 --> 01:03:14,816
[SPEAKER_26]: My understanding is that a debt exclusion provides additional funding for a capital project from taxpayers.

636
01:03:15,357 --> 01:03:18,679
[SPEAKER_26]: So the two slides about capital projects

637
01:03:19,399 --> 01:03:32,633
[SPEAKER_26]: that I assume are already included in your plan for our taxes between now and 2060, whatever you said, I don't understand why we're comparing a debt exclusion to that list of city services.

638
01:03:32,653 --> 01:03:41,382
[SPEAKER_26]: I feel like there's a lot of value judgments being made about money right now and about what's too expensive and about where we should spend our money.

639
01:03:42,523 --> 01:03:52,030
[SPEAKER_26]: I was pretty disappointed that the presentation had so much data around the senior citizens in our community and no data about the children in our community.

640
01:03:52,610 --> 01:04:06,380
[SPEAKER_26]: So I guess I would just like to hear from the mayor and her staff why we are comparing debt exclusion numbers to our capital planning budget and what you want the public to take away from this.

641
01:04:06,460 --> 01:04:08,862
[SPEAKER_26]: Cause I'm just like disappointed as a parent

642
01:04:13,623 --> 01:04:14,463
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you, Ellen.

643
01:04:15,043 --> 01:04:19,964
[SPEAKER_30]: We were asked by the committee to talk about the capital improvement plan.

644
01:04:20,404 --> 01:04:21,985
[SPEAKER_30]: We have a new six-year plan.

645
01:04:23,365 --> 01:04:32,406
[SPEAKER_30]: So what you saw were the major projects that we know of that need to be paid for in the next 10 to 20 years and how that models out.

646
01:04:32,947 --> 01:04:40,808
[SPEAKER_30]: The point of that is that we are being asked to put some of this debt on the general fund, and I

647
01:04:41,315 --> 01:05:00,967
[SPEAKER_30]: I think we had to outline that to show the committee and the residents that there's really not capacity if you want to do you as it is you already have to push the fire station and freedom way and some streets and sidewalks, because the modeling shows that we are just not going to be able to.

648
01:05:01,723 --> 01:05:11,209
[SPEAKER_30]: pay that back in the general fund alone, meaning most of the new school building is going to have to be on a debt exclusion.

649
01:05:11,709 --> 01:05:15,692
[SPEAKER_30]: So with showing that, we then showed that the 607, the 532, or the 440 will be the vote

650
01:05:20,655 --> 01:05:30,662
[SPEAKER_30]: depending on what numbers we pan out in the end, hopefully by the end of the fall, that will be the number that the taxpayers will know will be a debt exclusion.

651
01:05:30,882 --> 01:05:41,369
[SPEAKER_30]: And these are the facts to show what that would be per household, per apartment unit renter, per condo owner, per apartment complex owner.

652
01:05:42,630 --> 01:05:44,231
[SPEAKER_30]: per year, per month.

653
01:05:44,791 --> 01:05:46,232
[SPEAKER_30]: This is very fact-based.

654
01:05:46,653 --> 01:05:51,736
[SPEAKER_30]: I know people could be disappointed, but it's just a disappointment about the facts.

655
01:05:52,516 --> 01:06:01,142
[SPEAKER_30]: This is $800, $900 million proposed high school, and I'm just trying to show the facts so that the entire community knows where we're at.

656
01:06:01,162 --> 01:06:07,646
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Ellen.

657
01:06:08,146 --> 01:06:08,787
[SPEAKER_17]: Susan Wilson.

658
01:06:14,235 --> 01:06:15,083
[SPEAKER_11]: Hi, this is Susan Wilson.

659
01:06:15,103 --> 01:06:15,809
[SPEAKER_11]: Can you hear me okay?

660
01:06:16,636 --> 01:06:16,818
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes.

661
01:06:17,916 --> 01:06:18,356
[SPEAKER_11]: Great.

662
01:06:18,416 --> 01:06:19,477
[SPEAKER_11]: I live at 97 Winchester Street.

663
01:06:19,737 --> 01:06:20,937
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm a parent of three.

664
01:06:21,137 --> 01:06:29,061
[SPEAKER_11]: I agree with Ellen that I find it really upsetting how unrepresented children and, to a certain extent, parents are in this conversation.

665
01:06:29,081 --> 01:06:38,805
[SPEAKER_11]: You know, I think a lot of parents of small children have a hard time with these meetings and aren't necessarily as active in these conversations because they're just challenging and we're all overwhelmed.

666
01:06:38,865 --> 01:06:40,565
[SPEAKER_11]: But our kids are going to be at this high school.

667
01:06:41,206 --> 01:06:43,827
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think if we focus exclusively on

668
01:06:44,627 --> 01:06:47,590
[SPEAKER_11]: cemeteries and people on fixed incomes.

669
01:06:47,750 --> 01:06:54,297
[SPEAKER_11]: We're not engaging with the people who do vote in Medford, who move to Medford, who want to stay in Medford and pay taxes in Medford.

670
01:06:55,299 --> 01:06:58,562
[SPEAKER_11]: So, you know, the tone, I think, is just really, really kind of offensive.

671
01:06:59,888 --> 01:07:03,310
[SPEAKER_11]: I also wonder, I fully agree, this is about a debt exclusion.

672
01:07:03,330 --> 01:07:04,471
[SPEAKER_11]: This is not about the city's budget.

673
01:07:04,491 --> 01:07:08,914
[SPEAKER_11]: The city budget has issues like every city in our state and country at this time.

674
01:07:10,295 --> 01:07:11,296
[SPEAKER_11]: A debt exclusion is separate.

675
01:07:11,456 --> 01:07:14,558
[SPEAKER_11]: And to a certain extent, we haven't asked the voters if we want a debt exclusion yet.

676
01:07:14,578 --> 01:07:19,702
[SPEAKER_11]: So creating an incredibly negative sense based on facts that I don't think are true.

677
01:07:19,762 --> 01:07:22,864
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, I followed a certain amount of these meetings so far and

678
01:07:23,724 --> 01:07:24,905
[SPEAKER_11]: we don't have a final plan.

679
01:07:25,225 --> 01:07:27,367
[SPEAKER_11]: So without a final plan, we don't have final numbers.

680
01:07:27,467 --> 01:07:28,367
[SPEAKER_11]: Those numbers are guesses.

681
01:07:28,387 --> 01:07:29,328
[SPEAKER_11]: Those numbers are estimates.

682
01:07:29,368 --> 01:07:31,510
[SPEAKER_11]: We don't know what the MSBA is going to cover or not.

683
01:07:31,530 --> 01:07:32,410
[SPEAKER_11]: We have a guess.

684
01:07:33,291 --> 01:07:34,892
[SPEAKER_11]: But that's a really broad range.

685
01:07:34,952 --> 01:07:43,578
[SPEAKER_11]: So to have seven slides of incredibly granular detail about what numbers we all are anticipated to pay is premature at this time.

686
01:07:44,418 --> 01:07:49,982
[SPEAKER_11]: I think a lot of the conversations that need to happen between now and June 10th are about the pool and like other things.

687
01:07:50,082 --> 01:07:51,223
[SPEAKER_11]: And later we can kind of

688
01:07:51,763 --> 01:07:54,866
[SPEAKER_11]: figure out how we want to narrow it down to make this something that we can all afford.

689
01:07:55,446 --> 01:07:57,168
[SPEAKER_11]: But the truth is, this is something that we need.

690
01:07:57,608 --> 01:08:00,991
[SPEAKER_11]: So, you know, if we need this, how do we make it happen, right?

691
01:08:01,031 --> 01:08:05,495
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's part of the city's job is to help figure out where the money comes from.

692
01:08:05,575 --> 01:08:07,337
[SPEAKER_11]: Are there other ideas for revenue?

693
01:08:07,958 --> 01:08:10,900
[SPEAKER_11]: I think to a certain extent, the debt exclusion can cover a lot of this.

694
01:08:11,301 --> 01:08:13,743
[SPEAKER_11]: I think also on that one slide, what was it?

695
01:08:14,143 --> 01:08:15,845
[SPEAKER_11]: To get the school up to code,

696
01:08:16,585 --> 01:08:18,446
[SPEAKER_11]: is 500 million.

697
01:08:18,546 --> 01:08:23,168
[SPEAKER_11]: So, you know, I think there's also like a separate conversation of it's not just a new building that's expensive.

698
01:08:23,588 --> 01:08:30,571
[SPEAKER_11]: It's getting this building to be habitable and legally acceptable is also something that we as a city have to prioritize.

699
01:08:30,611 --> 01:08:31,771
[SPEAKER_11]: So how are we going to do that?

700
01:08:32,071 --> 01:08:41,435
[SPEAKER_11]: How are we going to put the different needs that we have in the school building currently into a new universe that's not this unsafe, unhospitable building?

701
01:08:42,395 --> 01:08:47,137
[SPEAKER_11]: So, you know, I think that's part of what the role of the city needs to be here is to help propose how we can afford this.

702
01:08:47,317 --> 01:08:48,237
[SPEAKER_11]: Are there new ideas?

703
01:08:48,337 --> 01:08:49,978
[SPEAKER_11]: Are there different places we can put things?

704
01:08:50,698 --> 01:08:59,921
[SPEAKER_11]: Are there creative ways that we can look at things that is outside of the scope of this high school committee and things that the citizens can't come up with on our own?

705
01:08:59,961 --> 01:09:09,024
[SPEAKER_11]: That's stuff that the city has access to, and I would have loved to hear more information about ideas to give Medford the school and the community center and all of these things that we deserve.

706
01:09:12,513 --> 01:09:13,153
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Susan.

707
01:09:14,814 --> 01:09:17,155
[SPEAKER_17]: Ada Gunning, you have three minutes.

708
01:09:22,598 --> 01:09:22,798
[SPEAKER_00]: Hi.

709
01:09:24,299 --> 01:09:25,960
[SPEAKER_00]: Ada Gunning, 40 Magoon Ave.

710
01:09:26,120 --> 01:09:27,401
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you for having me.

711
01:09:27,541 --> 01:09:37,846
[SPEAKER_00]: I wanted to thank everyone here for volunteering so much of your time over this past year on the building committee and for the mayor for putting together this presentation.

712
01:09:39,418 --> 01:09:41,300
[SPEAKER_00]: It was interesting to see all the numbers.

713
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:45,263
[SPEAKER_00]: I think for me, you know, I have kids who are five and seven.

714
01:09:45,283 --> 01:09:53,710
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm very excited and eager to have a high school that does not look like a prison for them and one that can have

715
01:09:54,375 --> 01:10:02,978
[SPEAKER_00]: a climate where they're not burning up or they're not freezing, where they can learn all the subjects they need to learn and get their educational needs met.

716
01:10:03,878 --> 01:10:09,680
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think what's missing for me is like, what is the city's vision for this high school?

717
01:10:09,700 --> 01:10:20,244
[SPEAKER_00]: I hear it coming from the building committee and it seems like a vision that we can be thinking through, like what are the pieces that we want to include in the high school?

718
01:10:20,264 --> 01:10:21,964
[SPEAKER_00]: What are the pieces we don't want to include in the high school?

719
01:10:22,004 --> 01:10:23,145
[SPEAKER_00]: But I'd love to hear from

720
01:10:24,365 --> 01:10:29,106
[SPEAKER_00]: The mayor, like, what would you like for the high school to have?

721
01:10:29,507 --> 01:10:34,468
[SPEAKER_00]: And what are you going to be doing to improve our funding streams?

722
01:10:35,128 --> 01:10:41,250
[SPEAKER_00]: How are you going to be presenting this to the public to gain support from the public to make sure that we get more people on board?

723
01:10:41,770 --> 01:10:44,551
[SPEAKER_00]: Because people in Medford, we want to be proud of our high school.

724
01:10:44,971 --> 01:10:49,272
[SPEAKER_00]: We want to be excited about this high school and we want your leadership to make this happen.

725
01:10:49,953 --> 01:10:57,435
[SPEAKER_00]: And then my other question is, I'm fairly familiar with like the lack of options.

726
01:10:58,939 --> 01:11:04,964
[SPEAKER_00]: around the city when it comes to buildings to house different programs.

727
01:11:05,824 --> 01:11:17,113
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'm just thinking through the different programs that are currently housed in the high school that have been discussed as maybe we want them in the high school, maybe we don't.

728
01:11:17,153 --> 01:11:21,397
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'd also love to hear from the mayor, like, where do you propose putting these programs?

729
01:11:21,917 --> 01:11:23,999
[SPEAKER_00]: How do you propose funding a move

730
01:11:24,379 --> 01:11:26,301
[SPEAKER_00]: of those programs to a different building.

731
01:11:26,581 --> 01:11:31,265
[SPEAKER_00]: I just would love to hear your proactive vision and how you're planning to sell this to the public.

732
01:11:31,485 --> 01:11:31,846
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

733
01:11:44,797 --> 01:11:45,357
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you, Ada.

734
01:11:45,517 --> 01:11:51,823
[SPEAKER_30]: I think that's been my stressor since the numbers have come out.

735
01:11:53,173 --> 01:11:54,474
[SPEAKER_30]: upwards of 900 million.

736
01:11:55,474 --> 01:12:04,338
[SPEAKER_30]: It's how do I first get this committee to reduce space and scope so that I can be

737
01:12:05,238 --> 01:12:10,200
[SPEAKER_30]: an advocate and knock on doors to ask people to support a high school.

738
01:12:10,760 --> 01:12:16,222
[SPEAKER_30]: So I put a number of space reductions proposals before this committee.

739
01:12:16,242 --> 01:12:23,544
[SPEAKER_30]: I think two or three meetings ago, we were going to start working through those.

740
01:12:24,464 --> 01:12:33,291
[SPEAKER_30]: But I agreed that it was the right thing to do to table those until after Labor Day, trying to listen to the project team on when the right time to do that is.

741
01:12:33,972 --> 01:12:37,735
[SPEAKER_30]: So, yes, we're always trying to increase revenue in the community.

742
01:12:37,755 --> 01:12:45,942
[SPEAKER_30]: I have 26 departments trying to manage 18 city buildings, plus all the school buildings.

743
01:12:47,523 --> 01:12:51,126
[SPEAKER_30]: I have the students and schools who I've really tried to

744
01:12:52,343 --> 01:12:56,585
[SPEAKER_30]: over my six and a half years really have tried to push the top of our list.

745
01:12:56,906 --> 01:13:02,388
[SPEAKER_30]: As you'll see, one year we gave I think nine to 10% increase to the schools.

746
01:13:03,369 --> 01:13:19,657
[SPEAKER_30]: But the reality is that I also have to worry about people on fixed incomes or people that are having a hard time affording groceries and gas or people, and I hear from people as I am out and about on the weekends and evenings,

747
01:13:20,686 --> 01:13:25,128
[SPEAKER_30]: family I recently talked to can't afford to take their family way on vacation.

748
01:13:25,188 --> 01:13:34,591
[SPEAKER_30]: So I, I have to worry about, um, all 60,000 residents, all 30 buildings, all 26 budgets.

749
01:13:35,371 --> 01:13:42,234
[SPEAKER_30]: Um, so my, my vision, if I, if I was just a resident shore, I can afford it.

750
01:13:42,274 --> 01:13:44,154
[SPEAKER_30]: And I would love to, um,

751
01:13:47,024 --> 01:13:50,588
[SPEAKER_30]: vote yes for the biggest and best high school in the nation.

752
01:13:51,429 --> 01:14:01,418
[SPEAKER_30]: But I am the only one that has to truly hear from and worry about every single person in this community.

753
01:14:02,279 --> 01:14:11,208
[SPEAKER_30]: And I've been very stressed about it because I too would love an extra playing field on top of a parking lot.

754
01:14:11,679 --> 01:14:15,081
[SPEAKER_30]: for our students, like if anybody knows me, it's like athletics.

755
01:14:16,182 --> 01:14:19,144
[SPEAKER_30]: Myself, my husband, my family, athletics, athletics, athletics.

756
01:14:19,724 --> 01:14:24,927
[SPEAKER_30]: But is that a luxury that we can afford or is it not?

757
01:14:25,007 --> 01:14:26,829
[SPEAKER_30]: And I think that's something we're going to have to decide.

758
01:14:27,969 --> 01:14:35,394
[SPEAKER_30]: When you talk about the city council and the school committee meeting in the, what I consider the school committee and city council chambers in city hall,

759
01:14:36,269 --> 01:14:40,471
[SPEAKER_30]: I feel like that's doing, uh, is serving its purpose.

760
01:14:40,491 --> 01:14:44,052
[SPEAKER_30]: And everybody has Monday nights for school committee, Tuesday, Wednesdays for city council.

761
01:14:44,572 --> 01:14:57,117
[SPEAKER_30]: So when I saw our school committee auditorium or chambers plus school committee conference room and school committee office in this build, I did propose to cut those things.

762
01:14:57,337 --> 01:15:03,640
[SPEAKER_30]: I think they're something that yes, we'd love to have space for our school committee, but again, a luxury.

763
01:15:04,895 --> 01:15:19,886
[SPEAKER_30]: So while I'm trying to increase revenue and trying to take care of our buildings and balance a budget and care about our students, of course, number one, but then our residents who really can't afford this.

764
01:15:20,607 --> 01:15:32,315
[SPEAKER_30]: And my mind going to, if we have more people that can't afford enough, that can't afford this and this debt exclusion feels that's, that's my fault too, that I'm not, that I am not speaking up.

765
01:15:32,536 --> 01:15:34,157
[SPEAKER_30]: And I really am trying to be.

766
01:15:34,778 --> 01:15:35,758
[SPEAKER_30]: fact-based tonight.

767
01:15:37,279 --> 01:15:52,423
[SPEAKER_30]: And I really am trusting in the team, but, you know, the full team, this committee, as well as the project team to guide us and make the tough decisions come the fall, because there's nothing I want more than to say, look at how we've reduced this.

768
01:15:52,703 --> 01:16:00,985
[SPEAKER_30]: Look what we're still offering our students and our, um, faculty, and let me knock on doors to support this.

769
01:16:01,693 --> 01:16:10,475
[SPEAKER_30]: Even though, you know, of course, some people are never going to be able to afford some of these numbers, but there's a lot of work that we have to do, and I'm just trying to get through.

770
01:16:11,303 --> 01:16:19,708
[SPEAKER_30]: that through to the committee and the project team that needs to make the tough decisions so we can be on our way to get a past debt exclusion.

771
01:16:20,128 --> 01:16:25,971
[SPEAKER_30]: That is like the underlying, we must get a past debt exclusion because this building is outdated.

772
01:16:26,952 --> 01:16:31,154
[SPEAKER_30]: It needs to be torn down and we need something new for our students and faculty.

773
01:16:31,755 --> 01:16:37,758
[SPEAKER_30]: But it needs to be something where we have the whole community in mind when we're doing.

774
01:16:40,432 --> 01:16:41,313
[SPEAKER_17]: Miranda Bresenio.

775
01:16:47,736 --> 01:16:49,958
[SPEAKER_06]: Hi, Miranda Bresenio to Taylor Street.

776
01:16:51,159 --> 01:17:07,008
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't have any kids in the schools, but I babysit for a lot of families in Medford, and so seeing the success of this project, especially for the families that I babysit for their young children, is something I'm invested in, and as someone who enjoys the Bistro, Medford Community Media, and whatnot as well.

777
01:17:07,469 --> 01:17:09,730
[SPEAKER_06]: I will say a lot of this feels very hypothetical,

778
01:17:10,189 --> 01:17:14,650
[SPEAKER_06]: and unhelpful to the process of actually moving a building choice forward.

779
01:17:15,591 --> 01:17:18,732
[SPEAKER_06]: I myself, I'm a renter, so I'm not seeing these tax bills myself.

780
01:17:19,272 --> 01:17:24,393
[SPEAKER_06]: But even when we passed the overrides two years ago, my rent was not significantly affected.

781
01:17:24,853 --> 01:17:39,918
[SPEAKER_06]: So I'm unclear on how an effect on renters is being calculated, especially because, you know, there's no rent control that we're mandating landlords cap or, you know, we, the city has no saying what landlords are charging for rent.

782
01:17:41,073 --> 01:17:58,702
[SPEAKER_06]: So even if a landlord was suggesting that an increase in their tax bill would mean they need to significantly increase rent, I think that's more of a comment on the irresponsible landlord for not budgeting rather than it is on the project price tag.

783
01:17:59,482 --> 01:18:09,747
[SPEAKER_06]: So I just hope that we can move past a sort of fear-based approach to this project and choose a building that meets the ed plan and meets the needs of students and the community.

784
01:18:10,285 --> 01:18:10,585
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

785
01:18:10,605 --> 01:18:13,668
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

786
01:18:14,449 --> 01:18:15,249
[SPEAKER_17]: Mike Mastrobone.

787
01:18:20,354 --> 01:18:23,356
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Mike Mastrobone, 73 Fulton Spring Road.

788
01:18:23,997 --> 01:18:24,477
[SPEAKER_01]: I'll be brief.

789
01:18:24,517 --> 01:18:29,221
[SPEAKER_01]: I think, first and foremost, nobody is pretending like this is a cheap project.

790
01:18:30,222 --> 01:18:32,424
[SPEAKER_01]: School buildings in 2026, they're just not cheap.

791
01:18:34,150 --> 01:18:38,793
[SPEAKER_01]: But we got to remember this is, we have to compare this to the cost of doing nothing, right?

792
01:18:38,853 --> 01:18:47,399
[SPEAKER_01]: Having our kids in a building that eats gas and that isn't heated or cooled properly.

793
01:18:47,419 --> 01:18:50,981
[SPEAKER_01]: I think calling it the biggest and most expensive project in the country, that's not fair.

794
01:18:51,862 --> 01:18:52,902
[SPEAKER_01]: That's not going to be the case.

795
01:18:53,363 --> 01:18:56,765
[SPEAKER_01]: Even comparing this to projects from five years ago is irrelevant, right?

796
01:18:56,785 --> 01:18:59,587
[SPEAKER_01]: Because construction costs have practically doubled or tripled.

797
01:19:00,227 --> 01:19:05,952
[SPEAKER_01]: the cost of bringing our current building up to code we've learned through this process is probably the most expensive thing we can do.

798
01:19:07,112 --> 01:19:12,517
[SPEAKER_01]: And so I just want to make one last point that I really appreciate sharing of financials.

799
01:19:12,577 --> 01:19:16,800
[SPEAKER_01]: I think a lot of residents are feeling like they want to get to that phase as fast as possible.

800
01:19:16,920 --> 01:19:25,187
[SPEAKER_01]: I think we'll be able to have much more healthy conversations about tradeoffs and costs and impacts once we get down to one

801
01:19:25,907 --> 01:19:30,010
[SPEAKER_01]: one design, but something that I'd like to see in future presentations from the team.

802
01:19:31,191 --> 01:19:38,976
[SPEAKER_01]: Mayor is context around projections like this so that everyday residents can understand what these big numbers mean.

803
01:19:38,996 --> 01:19:51,725
[SPEAKER_01]: I think there's a lot of power in sharing financial information, but without context, there needs to be a lot more teaching that's done in these presentations so that everyday residents can understand it, not just

804
01:19:52,505 --> 01:19:54,827
[SPEAKER_01]: you know, folks who live and breathe the stuff like your team.

805
01:19:54,867 --> 01:19:59,270
[SPEAKER_01]: So I appreciate that, but I'd love to see more of that in the future.

806
01:20:01,892 --> 01:20:02,312
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

807
01:20:02,633 --> 01:20:03,313
[SPEAKER_17]: Jessica Parks?

808
01:20:10,458 --> 01:20:11,819
[SPEAKER_13]: Jessica Parks, 38 Cory Street.

809
01:20:13,017 --> 01:20:13,237
Thank you.

810
01:20:13,817 --> 01:20:17,918
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much for the presentation, and I just want to follow up.

811
01:20:18,359 --> 01:20:27,061
[SPEAKER_13]: You know, we've heard about all of the costs and expenses the city is facing, and it is a lot, and I get that.

812
01:20:28,141 --> 01:20:33,723
[SPEAKER_13]: But one of the things I haven't heard, but I think I've heard asked a few times is about revenue.

813
01:20:34,263 --> 01:20:36,864
[SPEAKER_13]: And, you know, we saw a list of

814
01:20:37,704 --> 01:20:57,174
[SPEAKER_13]: the cost for the next few years, but do we have a list of the projects coming online in the next few years and the associated revenue that are associated with those projects that might kind of offset some of the expenses we're going to be facing?

815
01:20:58,015 --> 01:21:06,119
[SPEAKER_13]: Does that exist and is that possible to see in kind of relation to what we are going to be owing for many of these projects?

816
01:21:06,967 --> 01:21:07,447
[SPEAKER_13]: That's all.

817
01:21:07,587 --> 01:21:07,928
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

818
01:21:17,253 --> 01:21:20,895
[SPEAKER_17]: Mayor, did you want to answer that before I move on or should I move on?

819
01:21:23,737 --> 01:21:30,180
[SPEAKER_30]: We'll be posting our CIP plan so it outlines what will be done each year.

820
01:21:32,686 --> 01:21:39,628
[SPEAKER_30]: we just have to figure out when we'll be able to put, you know, something as big as say the fire station on.

821
01:21:40,348 --> 01:21:44,289
[SPEAKER_30]: So we evaluate that year by year based on what emergencies come up as well.

822
01:21:44,869 --> 01:21:51,191
[SPEAKER_30]: But basically everything on those two slides is, you know, needed within the next two to 10 years.

823
01:21:51,251 --> 01:21:53,611
[SPEAKER_30]: And it's just a matter of how much we can afford when.

824
01:22:11,806 --> 01:22:15,928
[SPEAKER_27]: I just wanted to say I'm really grateful for seeing all the numbers that were there.

825
01:22:16,668 --> 01:22:21,450
[SPEAKER_27]: That was very helpful to me to see for the foreseeable future what we're going to be dealing with financially.

826
01:22:22,630 --> 01:22:25,511
[SPEAKER_27]: The cost for Freedom Way kind of blew me away.

827
01:22:25,571 --> 01:22:27,812
[SPEAKER_27]: That was a very expensive proposition there.

828
01:22:28,572 --> 01:22:29,553
[SPEAKER_27]: The realism of

829
01:22:30,737 --> 01:22:35,141
[SPEAKER_27]: We have this sort of give and take with our schools currently.

830
01:22:36,142 --> 01:22:41,467
[SPEAKER_27]: The population is seeming to lessen in some spots.

831
01:22:42,208 --> 01:22:46,151
[SPEAKER_27]: Elementary schools that were built are all going to start needing more and more work.

832
01:22:46,632 --> 01:22:49,714
[SPEAKER_27]: So we have to be realistic about what we're spending money on.

833
01:22:50,696 --> 01:22:56,324
[SPEAKER_27]: There's no question that we need to look at the current state of Medford High School.

834
01:22:56,684 --> 01:22:59,648
[SPEAKER_27]: It was built, I believe, the first graduating class was 1974.

835
01:23:04,854 --> 01:23:09,039
[SPEAKER_27]: So it's an older building and when it was built it started with issues.

836
01:23:09,059 --> 01:23:11,722
[SPEAKER_27]: We've had to replace the roof on the gym multiple times.

837
01:23:12,183 --> 01:23:14,325
[SPEAKER_27]: We've had to fix the pool.

838
01:23:14,465 --> 01:23:18,430
[SPEAKER_27]: All of these expensive things that have taken place over the years.

839
01:23:19,071 --> 01:23:21,373
[SPEAKER_27]: Some of them very recently like the science labs.

840
01:23:22,114 --> 01:23:22,254
[SPEAKER_27]: So

841
01:23:23,473 --> 01:23:34,562
[SPEAKER_27]: As much as everybody wants to sit there and have this most pristine, state-of-the-art, large place for everybody to go to, it's just not realistic at this time, in my opinion.

842
01:23:34,762 --> 01:23:35,823
[SPEAKER_27]: I think it's a problem.

843
01:23:36,523 --> 01:23:42,067
[SPEAKER_27]: So that's just, I just wanted to say thank you for showing me all the numbers, all the stuff that's coming up.

844
01:23:42,428 --> 01:23:44,349
[SPEAKER_27]: I've been a homeowner in the city of Medford.

845
01:23:44,449 --> 01:23:46,090
[SPEAKER_27]: I've grown up in the city of Medford.

846
01:23:46,491 --> 01:23:47,892
[SPEAKER_27]: I went to Medford High School.

847
01:23:48,472 --> 01:23:51,455
[SPEAKER_27]: I go in there frequently, so I understand what we're dealing with.

848
01:23:52,449 --> 01:23:58,275
[SPEAKER_27]: but we have to be realistic about all of the expenses that are coming up, and we can't put all our eggs in one basket.

849
01:23:58,575 --> 01:23:58,915
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

850
01:23:58,935 --> 01:24:02,599
[SPEAKER_17]: Dean, can you give us your address for the record, please?

851
01:24:05,161 --> 01:24:06,463
[SPEAKER_27]: 19 Martin Street in Medford.

852
01:24:07,023 --> 01:24:07,424
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

853
01:24:08,124 --> 01:24:08,685
[SPEAKER_17]: Harrison Green?

854
01:24:17,997 --> 01:24:18,898
[SPEAKER_29]: Hi, Harrison Green.

855
01:24:19,078 --> 01:24:27,404
[SPEAKER_29]: I'm echoing an earlier, kind of much earlier comment.

856
01:24:30,906 --> 01:24:40,694
[SPEAKER_29]: For the presentation, I was hearing that the city doesn't have the debt capacity to fulfill the design and requirements that the building committee is developing right now.

857
01:24:41,334 --> 01:24:46,638
[SPEAKER_29]: So, which leads to my first question for the mayor is what priorities are higher than the requirements that will be cut?

858
01:24:47,235 --> 01:24:47,956
[SPEAKER_29]: on this project.

859
01:24:48,016 --> 01:24:50,558
[SPEAKER_29]: That's what I'm hearing from that presentation.

860
01:24:51,199 --> 01:24:57,745
[SPEAKER_29]: And then secondly, the last bullet point of the presentation said that the city is looking into alternate sources of funding.

861
01:24:59,046 --> 01:25:04,671
[SPEAKER_29]: What are those and what are you expecting or hoping the outcome to be of those possible sources?

862
01:25:05,732 --> 01:25:05,932
[SPEAKER_29]: Thanks.

863
01:25:25,140 --> 01:25:29,985
[SPEAKER_17]: Mayor, did you want me to take the next question or did you have answers for Harrison?

864
01:25:30,565 --> 01:25:33,748
[SPEAKER_30]: Yeah, I'll have to rewatch.

865
01:25:33,828 --> 01:25:36,911
[SPEAKER_30]: I didn't catch what exactly what the questions were.

866
01:25:36,931 --> 01:25:39,854
[SPEAKER_17]: Okay.

867
01:25:41,415 --> 01:25:42,116
[SPEAKER_17]: Maria Daniels.

868
01:25:51,806 --> 01:25:54,488
[SPEAKER_25]: Hi, Maria Daniel, 67 West Street.

869
01:25:54,528 --> 01:25:55,028
[SPEAKER_25]: Can you hear me?

870
01:25:55,769 --> 01:25:55,969
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes.

871
01:25:57,090 --> 01:25:57,330
[SPEAKER_25]: Great.

872
01:25:57,550 --> 01:25:57,850
[SPEAKER_25]: Thanks.

873
01:25:58,231 --> 01:26:00,933
[SPEAKER_25]: I want to thank the committee for all your hard work to this point.

874
01:26:00,993 --> 01:26:06,237
[SPEAKER_25]: I also want to thank the mayor and her team for your hard work, too, and for the data you brought tonight.

875
01:26:07,457 --> 01:26:12,001
[SPEAKER_25]: And I want to make a comment about a false dichotomy that I'm hearing develop here.

876
01:26:14,362 --> 01:26:18,784
[SPEAKER_25]: First of all, you know, my sons both recently graduated from Medford High School.

877
01:26:19,284 --> 01:26:20,744
[SPEAKER_25]: I know many current students there now.

878
01:26:21,245 --> 01:26:32,169
[SPEAKER_25]: I know many students who have succeeded through the high school and the voc with the amazing teachers who are there with the amazing educational plan that's been developed and increased and improved over the past few years.

879
01:26:33,069 --> 01:26:39,052
[SPEAKER_25]: I just want to say that for the record, and I think this hellhole narrative is incorrect.

880
01:26:39,616 --> 01:26:49,981
[SPEAKER_25]: So the person who spoke up before and said that she didn't want to send her elementary students there because the school is a hellhole is just not true.

881
01:26:51,182 --> 01:26:59,486
[SPEAKER_25]: There are parts of the school I would never want to set foot in again because I think they're unsafe, particularly the girls' locker room, if anyone wants to go see a really

882
01:26:59,986 --> 01:27:02,467
[SPEAKER_25]: horrible corner of Medford, you can go there.

883
01:27:03,648 --> 01:27:10,350
[SPEAKER_25]: But I think the other side of the narrative that's not correct is the one that says we can't afford a new school.

