[SPEAKER_04]: They are half the efficiency of roof and ground mounted, but we may have to

1550
02:45:52,773 --> 02:46:01,479
[SPEAKER_04]: at least discuss and look and address those as part of the solution to make an educated decision.

1551
02:46:01,700 --> 02:46:01,940
[SPEAKER_04]: Next.

1552
02:46:04,882 --> 02:46:18,172
[SPEAKER_04]: So in terms of how do we get to the net zero energy, and for you to understand a bit what that means, we talked about the energy use per square foot, the 35 EUI.

1553
02:46:20,633 --> 02:46:36,185
[SPEAKER_04]: So we would have to design a system that produces as much energy as what the school requires under that 35 EUI, which is close to 6.2 megawatt system.

1554
02:46:36,765 --> 02:46:40,768
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's what we've assessed in the percentage I showed earlier in the square footage.

1555
02:46:42,330 --> 02:46:42,590
[SPEAKER_04]: Next.

1556
02:46:45,130 --> 02:46:49,313
[SPEAKER_04]: So what we've been talking about up to date is the operational carbon.

1557
02:46:49,453 --> 02:46:52,996
[SPEAKER_04]: The energy use of your building represents operational carbon.

1558
02:46:53,736 --> 02:46:56,919
[SPEAKER_04]: And another component of your building are the materials.

1559
02:46:57,299 --> 02:47:01,322
[SPEAKER_04]: And those do hold and represent embodied carbon.

1560
02:47:02,923 --> 02:47:07,326
[SPEAKER_04]: The way we look at this for projects is we look at it as total carbon.

1561
02:47:07,526 --> 02:47:11,609
[SPEAKER_04]: It's important to look at both operational and embodied carbon combined.

1562
02:47:12,975 --> 02:47:24,183
[SPEAKER_04]: there's a perception or an understanding that existing buildings have embodied carbon and new buildings create embodied carbon, right?

1563
02:47:24,383 --> 02:47:25,464
[SPEAKER_04]: New embodied carbon.

1564
02:47:26,184 --> 02:47:33,269
[SPEAKER_04]: And so we're going to look at this next slide, which represents, oh, I'm sorry, excuse me.

1565
02:47:34,490 --> 02:47:37,952
[SPEAKER_04]: The next slide represents the embodied carbon analysis criteria.

1566
02:47:37,993 --> 02:47:41,395
[SPEAKER_04]: So again, we compared option B,

1567
02:47:42,572 --> 02:47:48,876
[SPEAKER_04]: 1.2 and option D1.1, with the understanding that B1.2 is a renovation addition.

1568
02:47:49,016 --> 02:47:50,997
[SPEAKER_04]: So it's a full gut renovation.

1569
02:47:51,037 --> 02:47:55,299
[SPEAKER_04]: We're not keeping everything in the building, mostly retaining the structure.

1570
02:47:55,319 --> 02:48:03,124
[SPEAKER_04]: We, you know, by code and for the net zero goal, we're highly insulating the enclosure.

1571
02:48:04,624 --> 02:48:06,065
[SPEAKER_04]: There's going to be a new interior.

1572
02:48:06,586 --> 02:48:09,067
[SPEAKER_04]: And we also included the modular classroom.

1573
02:48:10,160 --> 02:48:17,787
[SPEAKER_04]: And then at the other end of the spectrum for the options, we have the new construction, D1.1, which is 610,000 square feet.

1574
02:48:18,988 --> 02:48:24,113
[SPEAKER_04]: In this option, we've looked at low embodied carbon concrete, steel and insulation.

1575
02:48:24,133 --> 02:48:32,641
[SPEAKER_04]: And then we have an option within this option that looks at about 10 to 15% mass timber structure.

1576
02:48:33,362 --> 02:48:33,562
[SPEAKER_04]: Next.

1577
02:48:37,727 --> 02:48:44,032
[SPEAKER_04]: So here's the sort of comparison between the existing building and B1.2.

1578
02:48:44,352 --> 02:48:51,638
[SPEAKER_04]: And we actually did each option because we have operational carbon for ground source heat pump and air to water heat pump.

1579
02:48:52,439 --> 02:48:55,442
[SPEAKER_04]: So we did each for both design option.

1580
02:48:57,163 --> 02:48:59,505
[SPEAKER_04]: The embodied carbon is measured over 30 years.

1581
02:49:02,259 --> 02:49:12,250
[SPEAKER_04]: And so the operational carbon that we talked about, the 35 EUI, that's multiplied by 30 years.

1582
02:49:12,551 --> 02:49:16,896
[SPEAKER_04]: The carbon emissions equivalent from those are multiplied for 30 years.

1583
02:49:18,097 --> 02:49:19,498
[SPEAKER_04]: Since we have different

1584
02:49:20,484 --> 02:49:34,358
[SPEAKER_04]: square footage areas between the existing, the B1.2 and the D1.1, we have brought down this total carbon per square foot so that we were measuring sort of apples to apples here.

1585
02:49:35,499 --> 02:49:41,565
[SPEAKER_04]: So the existing building here, so the orange sections is the embodied carbon, the materials

1586
02:49:43,695 --> 02:49:48,880
[SPEAKER_04]: carbon, and then the blue sections, the operational carbon that represent the energy use.

1587
02:49:49,721 --> 02:49:59,290
[SPEAKER_04]: The existing building, as you can see, has embodied carbon that's existing, so it's a negative because it's already there.

1588
02:49:59,451 --> 02:50:02,454
[SPEAKER_04]: It's been created 50 years ago, 55 years ago, and so it's a negative.

1589
02:50:08,802 --> 02:50:12,644
[SPEAKER_04]: But then the building is not that efficient.

1590
02:50:13,064 --> 02:50:20,707
[SPEAKER_04]: So when you look at the operational carbon, it outweighs the design options.

1591
02:50:22,190 --> 02:50:37,649
[SPEAKER_04]: The B1.2 is embodied carbon, as you can see here is slightly, if not a bit, it's because of the classrooms, because the modular classroom, it's slightly higher than D1.1.

1592
02:50:39,962 --> 02:50:50,230
[SPEAKER_04]: And where you see the hatched area, the orange hatched area, that shows the impact of that 10 to 15% mass timber.

1593
02:50:50,250 --> 02:51:01,819
[SPEAKER_04]: So there's a way to slightly reduce, depending on how much mass timber we can include in the project, there's a way to reduce embodied carbon in the D1.1.

1594
02:51:02,999 --> 02:51:06,842
[SPEAKER_04]: A little bit more, not as much applicable to D1.2.

1595
02:51:09,860 --> 02:51:20,184
[SPEAKER_04]: And then in terms of the B1, the ground source heat pump and the air source heat pump, the ground source heat pump is a bit lower, 122 versus 126.

1596
02:51:20,905 --> 02:51:25,547
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's because of the efficiency of the ground source heat pump versus the air to water.

1597
02:51:26,107 --> 02:51:30,609
[SPEAKER_04]: Same thing with the 1.1.

1598
02:51:32,569 --> 02:51:38,712
[SPEAKER_04]: And the hatch blue at the top is just the equivalent of that hatch

1599
02:51:41,505 --> 02:51:46,869
[SPEAKER_04]: Orange, that's sort of the total that comes down because the orange would come down.

1600
02:51:47,189 --> 02:51:50,352
[SPEAKER_04]: It's the reduction from the mass timber.

1601
02:51:52,814 --> 02:51:59,100
[SPEAKER_04]: So that's it in a nutshell for total carbon in LCCA.

1602
02:51:59,120 --> 02:52:02,783
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you Martine.

1603
